TY  - JOUR
T1  - Costs of Job Rotation: Evidence from Mandatory Loan Officer Rotation
AU  - Bhowal, Subhendu
AU  - Subramanian, Krishnamurthy
AU  - Tantri, Prasanna
Y1  - 2020/06/03
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2020.3628
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2020.3628
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 2075
EP  - 2095
VL  - 67
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Job rotation inside an organization creates two conflicting effects. It disciplines agents by creating the fear that their successors may discover and report their hidden information. Thus, the agent takes actions that align with the principal?s objective. However, job rotation can create a moral hazard problem. If information is soft and therefore, nonverifiable, the principal cannot attribute blame to the agent or the successor. Agents shirk, thereby hurting performance. Thus, the importance of disciplining versus moral hazard effects depends on the availability of hard information. Using unique loan-level data, we show that job rotation hinders performance when the information is soft. This paper was accepted by Giesecke Kay, finance.
AB  - Job rotation inside an organization creates two conflicting effects. It disciplines agents by creating the fear that their successors may discover and report their hidden information. Thus, the agent takes actions that align with the principal?s objective. However, job rotation can create a moral hazard problem. If information is soft and therefore, nonverifiable, the principal cannot attribute blame to the agent or the successor. Agents shirk, thereby hurting performance. Thus, the importance of disciplining versus moral hazard effects depends on the availability of hard information. Using unique loan-level data, we show that job rotation hinders performance when the information is soft. This paper was accepted by Giesecke Kay, finance.
