T1  - Product Price Risk and Liquidity Management: Evidence from the Electricity Industry
AU  - Lin, Chen
AU  - Schmid, Thomas
AU  - Weisbach, Michael S.
Y1  - 2020/04/27
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2020.3579
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2020.3579
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 2519
EP  - 2540
VL  - 67
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Product price risk is a potentially important factor for firms? liquidity management. A natural place to evaluate the impact of this risk on liquidity management is the electricity industry, because producing firms face substantial price volatility in wholesale markets. Empirically, higher volatility of electricity prices leads to an increase in cash holdings, and this effect is robust to instrumenting for price risk using weather volatility. Cash increases more with price risk in firms using inflexible production technologies and those that cannot easily hedge electricity prices, indicating that operating flexibility and hedging are substitutes for liquidity management. This paper was accepted by Karl Diether, finance.
AB  - Product price risk is a potentially important factor for firms? liquidity management. A natural place to evaluate the impact of this risk on liquidity management is the electricity industry, because producing firms face substantial price volatility in wholesale markets. Empirically, higher volatility of electricity prices leads to an increase in cash holdings, and this effect is robust to instrumenting for price risk using weather volatility. Cash increases more with price risk in firms using inflexible production technologies and those that cannot easily hedge electricity prices, indicating that operating flexibility and hedging are substitutes for liquidity management. This paper was accepted by Karl Diether, finance.
